Primarily view GPX files from either Google Maps or
https://gpx.studio.  Did not try it with Garmin which
is probably a pity since the primary users of GPX files
these days are those with Garmin equipment.

Spent quite a bit of time trying to figure out if I could color
code the different waypoints and tracks to make it easier for
the viewer to figure out which route they were looking at.

Sadly, the GPX spec itself does not directly handle color,
so any solution would be extension dependent and therefore
depend on the viewer.

Most of the testing was done with Google Maps which (surprise)
prefers .kml files since Google controls the .kml spec.

I was unable to find a spec that Google Maps recognized with
.gpx files and since Google maps has no ability to export
anything other than .kml files, I have no idea what (if any)
extension it might use.

And at this point, since I am the only user, I simply don't
care.  I'm all for full generality until it actually requires
work.

Programmer leaves in a huff.
